abstract: The Los Angeles Dodgers would rather earn a World Series trophy on their own than accept any scraps from the Houston Astros or Boston Red Sox, the teams that beat them in 2017 and '18.
snippet: The Los Angeles Dodgers would rather earn a World Series trophy on their own than accept any scraps from the Houston Astros or Boston Red Sox, the teams that beat them in 2017 and '18.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — The Los Angeles Dodgers would rather earn a World Series trophy on their own than accept any scraps from the Houston Astros or Boston Red Sox, the teams that beat them in 2017 and '18.
headline_main: Several Dodgers Go Public, Peeved by Astros' Cheating Scam
headline_print_headline: Several Dodgers Go Public, Peeved by Astros' Cheating Scam

abstract: Paying attention to the impeachment trial this week? Us too. But here are 7 things that happened on the campaign trail you may have missed.
snippet: Paying attention to the impeachment trial this week? Us too. But here are 7 things that happened on the campaign trail you may have missed.
lead_paragraph: The Iowa caucuses are just around the corner — but with the impeachment trial underway in Washington, the presidential campaign is in a strange sort of suspended animation.

abstract: In the run-up to the U.S. 2020 presidential election, many Democratic White House contenders have argued in favor of either breaking up or tightening regulation of companies such as Facebook Inc, Alphabet Inc's Google and Amazon.com Inc.
snippet: In the run-up to the U.S. 2020 presidential election, many Democratic White House contenders have argued in favor of either breaking up or tightening regulation of companies such as Facebook Inc, Alphabet Inc's Google and Amazon.com Inc.
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - In the run-up to the U.S. 2020 presidential election, many Democratic White House contenders have argued in favor of either breaking up or tightening regulation of companies such as Facebook Inc, Alphabet Inc's Google and Amazon.com Inc.
headline_main: Where U.S. Presidential Candidates Stand on Breaking Up Big Tech
